json.author: Humans of New York
json.text: Last night someone asked me what part of Dear New York I’m proudest of; this was hard to answer. But I can tell you what’s filled my heart the most. Many in the press are calling it ‘The Children’s Exhibit,’ because Dear New York’s Vanderbilt Hall features the work of six hundred NYC student artists. Each student was asked to photograph and write about someone who has made a difference in their lives. Some of these artists are as young as four, and their photography might not be the most technically polished, but there is a striking intimacy that can only come from photographing someone you love. The written profiles which accompany the photographs are extremely touching, and collectively represent the millions of invisible, unsung heroes that form the bedrock of NYC’s community. It’s not the mayors and the movie stars that form the heart of this city. It’s the mothers, the fathers, the teachers, the social workers, and the millions of other people who show up every day in the lives of others. One reason the ‘Children’s Exhibit’ lands so deeply is that its amplified by a sister exhibition featuring eleven highly notable NYC photographers. Among them are living legends such as @jamelshabazz , a trailblazer in street portraiture. As well as Gugenheim Fellow @sarabennettbrooklyn , a former public defender who profiles formerly-incarcerated women. The two exhibits are blended seamlessly in an innovative, immersive design by @davidkorins . The most beautiful part of these blended exhibits is that all 611 artists— young and old, beginning and established— have been given the same museum-quality framing and presentation. The result is an egalitarian, non-hierarchical ode to the diversity, humanity, and community of this city.  The exhibit has been overflowing all week, from open to close, and I’m not sure I’ve ever seen an art installation elicit so much emotion. Dear New York closes on Sunday. For everyone who attends the final Sunday, you will be able to meet all eleven featured professional artists, who will be there to greet visitors between 2 pm and 5 pm.

json.text: “I’ve decided to go back to school today; I was just accepted into college, and I made the decision to enroll. I happened to be wearing my Coney Island shirt, so I decided to come out here and sit by the water. I used to come out here all the time. For many years I was in an extremely difficult marriage. I’d never say anything hurtful about my ex-wife, because there’s still a lot of love there— but there were times when I had to get away. And this is where I’d go. I ended up leaving the marriage right before the pandemic. I had to completely start over. I went from having my own apartment, and having all the things you’re supposed to have, to sleeping on a mattress on the floor. I never stopped teaching my voice and music lessons. I was still expanding, still growing. But I went through a lot of hardship. There was so much responsibility on me. My mother is 94; she has dementia. I was taking care of her too. For the longest time I’ve never had any room for something going on in my own life. So this is a very big thing for me—going back to school. I’m going to major in social work because I’d like to introduce a therapy element to my voice lessons. If I’m being honest, part of the reason is I need more clients. I’m not somebody who has a big retirement saved. I’m turning 65 soon and I’m no longer very competitive in an ageist music world. So money is part of it. But also, voice lessons are such a wonderful tool for self-actualization. I’ve noticed when people are learning to sing, they come up against so many things that are holding them back. They’ll meet with embarrassment. They’ll meet their inner critic. They’ll have moments where they think: that’s too loud, that’s too shrill. But they have to push past it. Because In order to fill the room, you first need a sense of being worthy enough to express yourself. You can’t say: I’m going to sing like this person. No, you’re going to sound like you. There are tools you can learn to sound like the best version of you, but you will sound like you. And it’s such a privilege to be present when people discover that for the first time: you can sing just like yourself, and it can be beautiful.”

json.author: Humans of New York
json.text: The first copies of Dear New York have arrived. This one is deeply personal; holding it in my hand is like holding three years of my life. it opens with a longform HONY story— think Tanqueray, think Detra, think Venus— except this time it’s the story of my own attempt to capture the people of this city. The book then expands into four hundred full-color portraits and stories. Unlike previous Humans of New York books: 75 percent of these stories have not been shared online. Dear New York was lovingly created to be the most special thing that’s ever come out of Humans of New York. It will make you think, it will make you laugh, it will make you cry. It’s my love letter to this city, and I can’t wait to share it with you this October. But if you could do me a favor: if you think you’ll be getting Dear New York this fall, consider locking in your order now. Preorders have never been more crucial to helping launch a book into the world. The book has yet to be heavily discounted, but I know Amazon and Barnes and Noble specifically will retroactively apply the inevitable future discounts to your order. Thanks everyone! Link in bio.

json.author: Humans of New York
json.text: How does a two-week art installation about community grow into something like this? I think it’s because people are tired of ‘connecting’ through screens. Nobody wants to live in a metaverse, whatever the hell that is. We don’t want to become passive consumers of songs that ‘seem’ human, art that ‘seems’ human, friends that ‘seem’ human. None of this stuff is what we need. We need to create. We need to connect. We need to serve other people if we’re going to have any sort of place or belonging in this world. If humanity is going to thrive— and if art is going to thrive – there is only one place for it to go: the real world. Dear New York was founded upon the increasingly rare belief that humanity is pretty freaking amazing. This isn’t a perfect world. Every day the media brings us new examples of glaring injustice and senseless violence. We still have much work to do. But while we do the work, let us not forget how much love there is in this world. In New York City alone, in a single day, there are millions of stories of people taking care of each other. These stories don’t make the evening news, but they’re no less real. And when you sum it all up—the good and the bad – humanity is still worth fighting for. It’s still something to celebrate. Dear New York will close tomorrow at 8 pm, with a short choral performance by hundreds of children from @ypcofnyc .

json.author: Humans of New York
json.text: I’d like to conclude with one final story that I think captures the spirit of Dear New York. During the final hour before Sunday’s closing ceremony there was no performer scheduled on the Steinway Concert Grand, so I loudly invited everyone in the crowd to take a turn. About six or seven random New Yorkers stepped forward, bravely volunteering for this once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to play the world’s finest piano for a huge crowd of people in Grand Central Station. It was such a joyous and communal experience. Each person played one song. Everyone was at-least-a-little nervous, but everyone nailed it under the brightest possible spotlight. Eventually one of the producers whispered that it was time to wrap up, but before I could tell everyone ‘Goodnight,’ I noticed the tiniest little hand being raised. It belonged to a six-year-old girl wearing a denim jacket, sparkly cowboy boots, and a small plastic princess crown. I knelt down and asked her name; she told me ‘Charlotte.’ I asked Charlotte if she wanted a chance to play, and she nodded with conviction. Her mother— half-proud, half-terrified—quickly told me that Charlotte had a keyboard at home, but had never played piano before. This small distinction did not bother Charlotte one bit. With the confidence of Liberace, she marched up to the Steinway, took a seat, and played piano for the very first time, in front of hundreds of people. I’m not sure anyone beyond the first row could hear it. But I am sure that everyone could feel it. Immediately following her performance, two hundred young singers from The Young People’s Chorus of New York City brought Dear New York to a close with an epic performance. (Video clip in carousel.) Thank you Charlotte, thank you @ypcofnyc, and thank you everyone, for being such an important part of Dear New York.

json.caption: “I’ve decided to go back to school today; I was just accepted into college, and I made the decision to enroll. I happened to be wearing my Coney Island shirt, so I decided to come out here and sit by the water. I used to come out here all the time. For many years I was in an extremely difficult marriage. I’d never say anything hurtful about my ex-wife, because there’s still a lot of love there— but there were times when I had to get away. And this is where I’d go. I ended up leaving the marriage right before the pandemic. I had to completely start over. I went from having my own apartment, and having all the things you’re supposed to have, to sleeping on a mattress on the floor. I never stopped teaching my voice and music lessons. I was still expanding, still growing. But I went through a lot of hardship. There was so much responsibility on me. My mother is 94; she has dementia. I was taking care of her too. For the longest time I’ve never had any room for something going on in my own life. So this is a very big thing for me—going back to school. I’m going to major in social work because I’d like to introduce a therapy element to my voice lessons. If I’m being honest, part of the reason is I need more clients. I’m not somebody who has a big retirement saved. I’m turning 65 soon and I’m no longer very competitive in an ageist music world. So money is part of it. But also, voice lessons are such a wonderful tool for self-actualization. I’ve noticed when people are learning to sing, they come up against so many things that are holding them back. They’ll meet with embarrassment. They’ll meet their inner critic. They’ll have moments where they think: that’s too loud, that’s too shrill. But they have to push past it. Because In order to fill the room, you first need a sense of being worthy enough to express yourself. You can’t say: I’m going to sing like this person. No, you’re going to sound like you. There are tools you can learn to sound like the best version of you, but you will sound like you. And it’s such a privilege to be present when people discover that for the first time: you can sing just like yourself, and it can be beautiful.”

json.caption: The first copies of Dear New York have arrived. This one is deeply personal; holding it in my hand is like holding three years of my life. it opens with a longform HONY story— think Tanqueray, think Detra, think Venus— except this time it’s the story of my own attempt to capture the people of this city. The book then expands into four hundred full-color portraits and stories. Unlike previous Humans of New York books: 75 percent of these stories have not been shared online. Dear New York was lovingly created to be the most special thing that’s ever come out of Humans of New York. It will make you think, it will make you laugh, it will make you cry. It’s my love letter to this city, and I can’t wait to share it with you this October. But if you could do me a favor: if you think you’ll be getting Dear New York this fall, consider locking in your order now. Preorders have never been more crucial to helping launch a book into the world. The book has yet to be heavily discounted, but I know Amazon and Barnes and Noble specifically will retroactively apply the inevitable future discounts to your order. Thanks everyone! Link in bio.

json.caption: How does a two-week art installation about community grow into something like this? I think it’s because people are tired of ‘connecting’ through screens. Nobody wants to live in a metaverse, whatever the hell that is. We don’t want to become passive consumers of songs that ‘seem’ human, art that ‘seems’ human, friends that ‘seem’ human. None of this stuff is what we need. We need to create. We need to connect. We need to serve other people if we’re going to have any sort of place or belonging in this world. If humanity is going to thrive— and if art is going to thrive – there is only one place for it to go: the real world. Dear New York was founded upon the increasingly rare belief that humanity is pretty freaking amazing. This isn’t a perfect world. Every day the media brings us new examples of glaring injustice and senseless violence. We still have much work to do. But while we do the work, let us not forget how much love there is in this world. In New York City alone, in a single day, there are millions of stories of people taking care of each other. These stories don’t make the evening news, but they’re no less real. And when you sum it all up—the good and the bad – humanity is still worth fighting for. It’s still something to celebrate. Dear New York will close tomorrow at 8 pm, with a short choral performance by hundreds of children from @ypcofnyc .

json.caption: I’d like to conclude with one final story that I think captures the spirit of Dear New York. During the final hour before Sunday’s closing ceremony there was no performer scheduled on the Steinway Concert Grand, so I loudly invited everyone in the crowd to take a turn. About six or seven random New Yorkers stepped forward, bravely volunteering for this once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to play the world’s finest piano for a huge crowd of people in Grand Central Station. It was such a joyous and communal experience. Each person played one song. Everyone was at-least-a-little nervous, but everyone nailed it under the brightest possible spotlight. Eventually one of the producers whispered that it was time to wrap up, but before I could tell everyone ‘Goodnight,’ I noticed the tiniest little hand being raised. It belonged to a six-year-old girl wearing a denim jacket, sparkly cowboy boots, and a small plastic princess crown. I knelt down and asked her name; she told me ‘Charlotte.’ I asked Charlotte if she wanted a chance to play, and she nodded with conviction. Her mother— half-proud, half-terrified—quickly told me that Charlotte had a keyboard at home, but had never played piano before. This small distinction did not bother Charlotte one bit. With the confidence of Liberace, she marched up to the Steinway, took a seat, and played piano for the very first time, in front of hundreds of people. I’m not sure anyone beyond the first row could hear it. But I am sure that everyone could feel it. Immediately following her performance, two hundred young singers from The Young People’s Chorus of New York City brought Dear New York to a close with an epic performance. (Video clip in carousel.) Thank you Charlotte, thank you @ypcofnyc, and thank you everyone, for being such an important part of Dear New York.

Last night someone asked me what part of Dear New York I’m proudest of; this was hard to answer. But I can tell you what’s filled my heart the most. Many in the press are calling it ‘The Children’s Exhibit,’ because Dear New York’s Vanderbilt Hall features the work of six hundred NYC student artists. Each student was asked to photograph and write about someone who has made a difference in their lives. Some of these artists are as young as four, and their photography might not be the most technically polished, but there is a striking intimacy that can only come from photographing someone you love. The written profiles which accompany the photographs are extremely touching, and collectively represent the millions of invisible, unsung heroes that form the bedrock of NYC’s community. It’s not the mayors and the movie stars that form the heart of this city. It’s the mothers, the fathers, the teachers, the social workers, and the millions of other people who show up every day in the lives of others. One reason the ‘Children’s Exhibit’ lands so deeply is that its amplified by a sister exhibition featuring eleven highly notable NYC photographers. Among them are living legends such as @jamelshabazz , a trailblazer in street portraiture. As well as Gugenheim Fellow @sarabennettbrooklyn , a former public defender who profiles formerly-incarcerated women. The two exhibits are blended seamlessly in an innovative, immersive design by @davidkorins . The most beautiful part of these blended exhibits is that all 611 artists— young and old, beginning and established— have been given the same museum-quality framing and presentation. The result is an egalitarian, non-hierarchical ode to the diversity, humanity, and community of this city.  The exhibit has been overflowing all week, from open to close, and I’m not sure I’ve ever seen an art installation elicit so much emotion. Dear New York closes on Sunday. For everyone who attends the final Sunday, you will be able to meet all eleven featured professional artists, who will be there to greet visitors between 2 pm and 5 pm.

json.caption: “I’ve decided to go back to school today; I was just accepted into college, and I made the decision to enroll. I happened to be wearing my Coney Island shirt, so I decided to come out here and sit by the water. I used to come out here all the time. For many years I was in an extremely difficult marriage. I’d never say anything hurtful about my ex-wife, because there’s still a lot of love there— but there were times when I had to get away. And this is where I’d go. I ended up leaving the marriage right before the pandemic. I had to completely start over. I went from having my own apartment, and having all the things you’re supposed to have, to sleeping on a mattress on the floor. I never stopped teaching my voice and music lessons. I was still expanding, still growing. But I went through a lot of hardship. There was so much responsibility on me. My mother is 94; she has dementia. I was taking care of her too. For the longest time I’ve never had any room for something going on in my own life. So this is a very big thing for me—going back to school. I’m going to major in social work because I’d like to introduce a therapy element to my voice lessons. If I’m being honest, part of the reason is I need more clients. I’m not somebody who has a big retirement saved. I’m turning 65 soon and I’m no longer very competitive in an ageist music world. So money is part of it. But also, voice lessons are such a wonderful tool for self-actualization. I’ve noticed when people are learning to sing, they come up against so many things that are holding them back. They’ll meet with embarrassment. They’ll meet their inner critic. They’ll have moments where they think: that’s too loud, that’s too shrill. But they have to push past it. Because In order to fill the room, you first need a sense of being worthy enough to express yourself. You can’t say: I’m going to sing like this person. No, you’re going to sound like you. There are tools you can learn to sound like the best version of you, but you will sound like you. And it’s such a privilege to be present when people discover that for the first time: you can sing just like yourself, and it can be beautiful.”

json.caption: How does a two-week art installation about community grow into something like this? I think it’s because people are tired of ‘connecting’ through screens. Nobody wants to live in a metaverse, whatever the hell that is. We don’t want to become passive consumers of songs that ‘seem’ human, art that ‘seems’ human, friends that ‘seem’ human. None of this stuff is what we need. We need to create. We need to connect. We need to serve other people if we’re going to have any sort of place or belonging in this world. If humanity is going to thrive— and if art is going to thrive – there is only one place for it to go: the real world. Dear New York was founded upon the increasingly rare belief that humanity is pretty freaking amazing. This isn’t a perfect world. Every day the media brings us new examples of glaring injustice and senseless violence. We still have much work to do. But while we do the work, let us not forget how much love there is in this world. In New York City alone, in a single day, there are millions of stories of people taking care of each other. These stories don’t make the evening news, but they’re no less real. And when you sum it all up—the good and the bad – humanity is still worth fighting for. It’s still something to celebrate. Dear New York will close tomorrow at 8 pm, with a short choral performance by hundreds of children from @ypcofnyc .

json.caption: I’d like to conclude with one final story that I think captures the spirit of Dear New York. During the final hour before Sunday’s closing ceremony there was no performer scheduled on the Steinway Concert Grand, so I loudly invited everyone in the crowd to take a turn. About six or seven random New Yorkers stepped forward, bravely volunteering for this once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to play the world’s finest piano for a huge crowd of people in Grand Central Station. It was such a joyous and communal experience. Each person played one song. Everyone was at-least-a-little nervous, but everyone nailed it under the brightest possible spotlight. Eventually one of the producers whispered that it was time to wrap up, but before I could tell everyone ‘Goodnight,’ I noticed the tiniest little hand being raised. It belonged to a six-year-old girl wearing a denim jacket, sparkly cowboy boots, and a small plastic princess crown. I knelt down and asked her name; she told me ‘Charlotte.’ I asked Charlotte if she wanted a chance to play, and she nodded with conviction. Her mother— half-proud, half-terrified—quickly told me that Charlotte had a keyboard at home, but had never played piano before. This small distinction did not bother Charlotte one bit. With the confidence of Liberace, she marched up to the Steinway, took a seat, and played piano for the very first time, in front of hundreds of people. I’m not sure anyone beyond the first row could hear it. But I am sure that everyone could feel it. Immediately following her performance, two hundred young singers from The Young People’s Chorus of New York City brought Dear New York to a close with an epic performance. (Video clip in carousel.) Thank you Charlotte, thank you @ypcofnyc, and thank you everyone, for being such an important part of Dear New York.
